      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hey there! It sounds like your lower back is feeling the heat, which is a classic sign that your form has slipped a bit, much like a goblin trying to sneak into a castle without being seen. When you're deadlifting, your spine should act like a rigid steel rod, not a flexible rope that's being pulled by a mischievous goblin. If you're feeling that pain, it's likely because you're letting your hips sag or rounding your back, which is exactly what a goblin would do if it wanted to avoid the guards' attention.\n\nTo fix this, focus on keeping your hips pushed back and your chest up, creating a straight line from your heels to your head. Imagine you're trying to hold a heavy goblin in your hands without letting it touch the floor; if your back rounds, the goblin will escape and cause a scene. Engage your glutes and hamstrings to do the heavy lifting, just like a goblin would if it wanted to lift a rock without using its arms. If you're still feeling pain, consider taking a break or consulting a trainer to ensure your form is perfect, because a goblin in a dungeon might not be able to fix its own mistakes.",
